      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read all safety warnings and instructions before use.</strong> To reduce the risk of
        injury, the user must read and understand the safety material supplied with the tool and battery.
        Failure to follow warnings and instructions may result in fire, electric shock, and/or serious
        injury.
      </div>

      <h3>Required Personal Protective Equipment</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Safety glasses or goggles (always)</li>
        <li>Approved dust mask / respirator rated for fine particulate</li>
        <li>Hearing protection for extended use</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>General Practices</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep the work area clean and well lit; keep bystanders away while sanding.</li>
        <li>Remove the battery pack before changing the backing pad, abrasives, or accessories, and before any maintenance.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing, jewelry, or gloves that can catch in the moving pad. Tie back long hair.</li>
        <li>Maintain firm footing and balance; keep both hands controlling the tool.</li>
        <li>Always start the sander before contacting the workpiece and lift it off before releasing the trigger to avoid gouging.</li>
        <li>Secure the workpiece. Do not hold small pieces by hand against the pad.</li>
        <li>Use only Milwaukee 3" backing pads and accessories designed for this tool.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Dust hazard:</strong> Some dust created by power sanding contains chemicals known to
        cause cancer, birth defects, or other reproductive harm &mdash; for example lead from
        lead-based paint, crystalline silica from masonry, and arsenic/chromium from treated lumber.
        Work in a well-ventilated area, run the integrated dust collection or a vacuum, and wear an
        approved respirator.
      </div>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Battery safety:</strong> Charge only with the specified Milwaukee charger. Do not
        expose the battery to fire or temperatures above 50&deg;C (120&deg;F). Do not crush, puncture,
        or short the terminals. Store the battery out of metal-cluttered areas.
      </div>

