      <h2>Operation</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Insert a charged M12&trade; battery pack until it latches.</li>
        <li>Attach the appropriate mesh sanding disc to the hook-and-loop backing pad, centered so the dust-extraction holes line up. Add the interface sponge pad first when sanding contoured profiles.</li>
        <li>Connect the dust bag or attach a shop vacuum hose using the universal vacuum adapter.</li>
        <li>Select the speed setting for the material and finish &mdash; higher settings for fast stock removal, lower settings for fine finishing and delicate trim.</li>
        <li><strong>Start the sander before placing it on the work.</strong> Lower the spinning pad flat onto the surface.</li>
        <li>Let the tool&rsquo;s weight do the work &mdash; apply light, even pressure and keep the pad moving. Excess pressure slows the orbit and degrades the finish.</li>
        <li>Press the work-light button as needed to illuminate the work area in tight corners.</li>
        <li><strong>Lift the sander off the surface before releasing the trigger</strong> to prevent gouging or swirl marks.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Stain-grade finish:</strong> The 3/32" random-orbit motion is tuned to leave a clean,
        consistent surface suitable for staining. Step through grits in sequence (e.g. 80 &rarr; 120
        &rarr; 180 &rarr; 220) and avoid skipping more than one grade at a time.
      </div>

      <h2>Changing the Backing Pad</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Peel off any remaining abrasive disc and pad saver.</li>
        <li>Remove the screws securing the backing pad assembly to the spindle.</li>
        <li>Fit the new backing pad (44-52-1007) and the rubber pad brake (44-52-0974), seating them squarely on the spindle.</li>
        <li>Reinstall and tighten the screws, then reinstall the battery and verify the pad spins true.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Remove the battery pack before any cleaning or maintenance.</strong>
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Keep it clean:</strong> Blow dust off the tool and clear the dust-extraction holes in the backing pad regularly. Empty or replace the dust bag often.</li>
        <li><strong>Air vents:</strong> Keep the motor cooling vents clear of dust to prevent overheating.</li>
        <li><strong>Backing pad &amp; pad saver:</strong> Replace when the hook-and-loop loses grip or the pad face is worn. Use a pad saver to extend backing-pad life during aggressive sanding.</li>
        <li><strong>Contacts:</strong> Keep the battery terminals clean and dry.</li>
        <li><strong>Service:</strong> Any repair requiring the housing to be opened should be performed by a Milwaukee-authorized service facility. See the wiring diagram below for reference during authorized service.</li>
      </ul>

